{"id":"691bc2f2d2ed","content":"10 min read\nJust now\n\n--\n\nA beginner-friendly walkthrough for HTML Experiment 4 — where we finally let users talk back to our webpage.\n\nBefore We Start\nIn Experiment 1, you learned structure. In Experiment 2, links and media. In Experiment 3, tables — how to display structured data. But every page so far has been a one-way street: the website talks, the user just reads.\nForms flip that around. They’re how a website listens. Every time you’ve booked a hotel room, signed up for something, or searched Google, you’ve used a form. Experiment 4 is about learning to build that two-way conversation yourself.\nBy the end of this post, you’ll understand how to build:\n\n• A basic form structure\n\n• Properly linked labels\n\n• Multiple input types for different data\n\n• A select dropdown\n\n• A multi-line textarea\n\n• The right kind of button for the right job\n\n• A complete, combined hotel room booking form\nSame pattern as always: why it matters → how it works → code you can run. Let’s check in. 🛎️\n\n1. Form Structure Basics — The Container for User Input 📝\nWhy This Matters\nEvery input field, checkbox, and button you build in this experiment needs to live inside something that knows how to collect and send that data. That container is the <form> tag. Without it, your inputs are just decoration — nothing bundles them together, and nothing knows where to send what the user typed.\nForms are genuinely the backbone of interactive websites: login pages, search bars, checkout pages, contact forms, and — for us — a hotel booking page, are all built on this one tag.\nKey Attributes: action and method\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\nWhy GET vs POST matters for a hotel booking form specifically: you wouldn’t want a guest’s name, email, and phone number showing up as plain text in the browser’s URL bar (which is what GET does). POST Keeps that data out of the URL — the correct, safer choice for anything resembling personal information.\nCode: A Minimal Empty Form Skeleton\nhtml\n<form action=\"/submit-booking\" method=\"POST\">\n<!-- All our labels, inputs, and buttons will go here -->\n</form>That’s it — right now it does nothing visible, but it’s the container everything else in this post will live inside.\n💡 Pro Tip: During practice/development, you can leave action pointing to a placeholder like \"#\" or \"/submit-booking\" even if there's no real backend yet. You'll connect it to an actual server later — for now, focus on getting the structure right.\n\n2. Labels — The Most Skipped, Most Important Tag 🏷️\nWhy This Matters\nHere’s a mistake almost every beginner makes: typing a bit of text next to an input field and assuming that “labels” it.\nhtml\n<!-- Looks labeled, but isn't -->\nGuest Name: <input type=\"text\">Visually, this works. But structurally, the browser has no idea that “Guest Name” describes that specific input. A screen reader will read the input as an unlabeled text box. And here’s a subtle usability loss too: on a real, properly-linked label, clicking the label text itself focuses the input — genuinely helpful on mobile, where tapping a tiny checkbox is much harder than tapping the word next to it.\nThe fix is the <label> tag, connected to its input using matching for and id values.\nHow It Works\nhtml\n<label for=\"guestName\">Guest Name</label>\n<input type=\"text\" id=\"guestName\" name=\"guestName\">\n• The label’s for=\"guestName\" must exactly match the input's id=\"guestName\"\n\n• This creates a real, permanent connection — not just visual closeness\nCode: A Simple Labeled Text Input\nhtml\n<label for=\"guestName\">Guest Name</label>\n<input type=\"text\" id=\"guestName\" name=\"guestName\" placeholder=\"Enter your full name\">Now try clicking directly on the words “Guest Name” in a browser — the cursor jumps straight into the input box. That’s the label doing its job.\n⚠️ Common Mistake: Mismatched for and id values — even a small typo (for=\"guestname\" vs id=\"guestName\") silently breaks the connection, and you won't get an error message. Always double-check they match exactly, including capitalization.\n\n3. Input Fields — HTML’s Swiss-Army Knife Tag 🔧\nWhy This Matters\nYou might expect a different tag for every kind of data — one for names, one for emails, one for dates. HTML actually handles this more efficiently: there’s just one <input> tag, and its type attribute decides what kind of data it collects, what keyboard/UI the browser shows, and what basic validation happens automatically.\nThis is genuinely powerful — changing one word (type=\"email\" vs type=\"text\") gets you a different mobile keyboard, different validation, and a different meaning, all for free.\nKey Shared Attributes\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\n⚠️ Common Mistake: Forgetting the name attribute. The field might look totally normal on screen, but when the form is submitted, that input's data simply won't be included — it's the single most common \"why isn't my form working\" bug.\nInput Types for a Hotel Booking Form\nGuest Name — type=\"text\"\nhtml\n<label for=\"guestName\">Guest Name</label>\n<input type=\"text\" id=\"guestName\" name=\"guestName\" placeholder=\"e.g., Aditi Sharma\" required>Email Address — type=\"email\"\nUsing type=\"email\" instead of type=\"text\" makes the browser automatically check for a valid email pattern (something@something.something) before letting the form submit.\nhtml\n<label for=\"guestEmail\">Email Address</label>\n<input type=\"email\" id=\"guestEmail\" name=\"guestEmail\" placeholder=\"you@example.com\" required>Phone Number — type=\"tel\"\nhtml\n<label for=\"guestPhone\">Phone Number</label>\n<input type=\"tel\" id=\"guestPhone\" name=\"guestPhone\" placeholder=\"+91 98765 43210\">On mobile devices, type=\"tel\" pulls up the numeric phone keypad instead of the full keyboard — a small detail that makes a big difference in usability.\nCheck-in and Check-out Dates — type=\"date\"\nhtml\n<label for=\"checkinDate\">Check-in Date</label>\n<input type=\"date\" id=\"checkinDate\" name=\"checkinDate\" required>\n<label for=\"checkoutDate\">Check-out Date</label>\n<input type=\"date\" id=\"checkoutDate\" name=\"checkoutDate\" required>type=\"date\" gives the user a built-in calendar picker — no need to build your own or worry about people typing dates in ten different formats.\nNumber of Guests — type=\"number\" with min/max\nhtml\n<label for=\"guestCount\">Number of Guests</label>\n<input type=\"number\" id=\"guestCount\" name=\"guestCount\" min=\"1\" max=\"6\" value=\"1\">min and max stops a guest from typing something unrealistic like -3 or 500 guests for one room — basic validation, built right into the tag.\nRoom Type — type=\"radio\" (pick exactly one)\nRadio buttons are for when the user must choose exactly one option out of a small set. The key detail: all related radio buttons must share the same name, which is what tells the browser they belong to one group and only one can be selected.\nhtml\n<p>Room Type:</p>\n<input type=\"radio\" id=\"single\" name=\"roomType\" value=\"Single\">\n<label for=\"single\">Single</label>\n<input type=\"radio\" id=\"double\" name=\"roomType\" value=\"Double\">\n<label for=\"double\">Double</label>\n<input type=\"radio\" id=\"suite\" name=\"roomType\" value=\"Suite\">\n<label for=\"suite\">Suite</label>Add-on Services — type=\"checkbox\" (pick any number)\nUnlike radio buttons, checkboxes let the user select as many as they want — perfect for optional extras where none, some, or all could apply.\nhtml\n<p>Add-on Services:</p>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"breakfast\" name=\"addOns\" value=\"Breakfast\">\n<label for=\"breakfast\">Breakfast</label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"pickup\" name=\"addOns\" value=\"Airport Pickup\">\n<label for=\"pickup\">Airport Pickup</label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"lateCheckout\" name=\"addOns\" value=\"Late Checkout\">\n<label for=\"lateCheckout\">Late Checkout</label>Radio vs Checkbox — Quick Comparison\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\n💡 Pro Tip: Give each radio button and checkbox a unique id, but let all radios in the same group share one name. That's the difference between \"these are related choices\" and \"these are the same single field.\"\n\n4. The Select Dropdown — When You Have Too Many Choices 📜\nWhy This Matters\nRadio buttons are great for 2–4 options. But imagine using radio buttons for a Room Category choice with Standard, Deluxe, Executive, and Presidential Suite — and then imagine a hotel chain with 15 room categories. That’s a wall of buttons taking up the whole page.\nThe <select> dropdown solves this by collapsing many options into a single compact control that only expands when clicked — saving huge amounts of space.\nHow It Works\nhtml\n<label for=\"roomCategory\">Room Category</label>\n<select id=\"roomCategory\" name=\"roomCategory\">\n<option value=\"standard\">Standard</option>\n<option value=\"deluxe\" selected>Deluxe</option>\n<option value=\"executive\">Executive</option>\n<option value=\"presidential\">Presidential Suite</option>\n</select>\n• <select> is the dropdown container — it gets the id, name, and label like any other field\n\n• Each <option> is one choice inside it\n\n• The selected attribute marks which option shows by default, before the user picks anything\n💡 Pro Tip: Use selected on whichever option makes sense as your \"most common\" default — here, \"Deluxe\" being pre-selected can gently nudge guests toward it, a small but real UX decision.\nRadio vs Select — When to Use Which\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\n5. Textarea — When One Line Isn’t Enough 📄\nWhy This Matters\n<input type=\"text\"> is built for short, single-line answers — a name, an email. But what about something like \"any special requests?\" A guest might want to write two or three sentences: \"Please provide a room away from the elevator, and a crib for our infant.\" Cramming that into a single-line input is uncomfortable to type and read.\n<textarea> is a separate tag specifically designed for multi-line text input — it gives the user a resizable box instead of a single strip.\nKey Attributes\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\nCode: A Special Requests Field\nhtml\n<label for=\"specialRequests\">Special Requests / Notes</label>\n<textarea id=\"specialRequests\" name=\"specialRequests\" rows=\"4\" cols=\"40\" placeholder=\"Let us know about any special requirements...\"></textarea>Notice something different here compared to <input>: <textarea> is not self-closing. Whatever goes between <textarea> and </textarea> becomes the pre-filled starting text (leave it empty and only the placeholder shows).\n⚠️ Common Mistake: Writing <textarea placeholder=\"...\" /> as a self-closing tag like an <input>. Textarea doesn't work that way — always use an opening and closing tag pair.\n\n6. Buttons — Submit, Reset, or Just… Button? 🔘\nWhy This Matters\nNot every clickable button in a form should do the same thing. Submitting a booking, clearing the form, and (later, with JavaScript) something like “check availability” are three completely different actions — and HTML gives you a type attribute to tell buttons apart clearly.\nThe Three Button Types\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\nButton TypesWhy type=\"submit\" Is the Sneaky Default\nHere’s a detail that trips up a lot of beginners: if you write a <button> without specifying a type at all, it automatically behaves as type=\"submit\".\nhtml\n<button>Click Me</button> <!-- This secretly submits the form! -->If you had a “Show Room Photos” button meant to just toggle something visually (with JavaScript later), and you forgot to add type=\"button\", clicking it would submit the whole form unexpectedly — often refreshing or navigating the page. Always be explicit about your button's type.\nCode: Confirm Booking and Clear Form Buttons\nhtml\n<button type=\"submit\">Confirm Booking</button>\n<button type=\"reset\">Clear Form</button>⚠️ Common Mistake: Leaving out type=\"button\" on non-submit buttons. If it's not meant to submit or reset the form, always label it explicitly, or it will quietly default to submit.\n💡 Pro Tip: Use type=\"reset\" sparingly — it wipes out everything the user filled in, with no confirmation. For a long form like a booking page, some designers skip a reset button en"}